{"id":"2007.06112","submitter":"Terry Loring A","authors":"Terry Loring and Fredy Vides","title":"Computing Floquet Hamiltonians with Symmetries","comments":"25 pages, 13 figure, 14 ancillary files, primarily Matlab files.\n  Updated to have correct spelling of author names of authors in the Arxiv\n  metadata","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1063/5.0023028","report-no":null,"categories":"math.NA cs.NA math-ph math.FA math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Unitary matrices arise in many ways in physics, in particular as a time\nevolution operator. For a periodically driven system one frequently wishes to\ncompute a Floquet Hamilonian that should be a Hermitian operator $H$ such that\n$e^{-iTH}=U(T)$ where $U(T)$ is the time evolution operator at time\ncorresponding the period of the system. That is, we want $H$ to be equal to\n$-i$ times a matrix logarithm of $U(T)$. If the system has a symmetry, such as\ntime reversal symmetry, one can expect $H$ to have a symmetry beyond being\nHermitian.\n  We discuss here practical numerical algorithms on computing matrix logarithms\nthat have certain symmetries which can be used to compute Floquet Hamiltonians\nthat have appropriate symmetries. Along the way, we prove some results on how a\nsymmetry in the Floquet operator $U(T)$ can lead to a symmetry in a basis of\nFloquet eigenstates.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 12 Jul 2020 22:25:13 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 23 Jul 2020 22:17:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-12-02"}
